---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import PostAttribution from '../components/PostAttribution.astro';
import PostData from '../components/PostData.astro';
import featureImage from '../../../content/img/posts/presentations/aieng26/brain-bunny-tradeoff-background-v2.png';

const title = 'Fail fast, fix faster: AI Engineer Melbourne 2026 resources';
const slug = 'aieng26/';
const date = '2026-06-03 12:30:00+1000';
const excerpt = `Slides, benchmark code, model cards and references for
  Fail fast, fix faster at AI Engineer Melbourne 2026.`;
const tags = ['thinking', 'ai', 'development', 'agents', 'presentation'];
const featureimage = featureImage;

const data = {
  title,
  date,
  excerpt,
  slug,
  featureimage,
  large_title: false,
  tags,
  uri: slug,
};

const seo = {
  title: 'Fail fast, fix faster | AI Engineer Melbourne 2026',
  description: 'Resources for AJ Fisher\'s AI Engineer Melbourne 2026 talk.',
  image: featureImage,
  type: 'article',
};
---
<BaseLayout title="AI Engineer 2026 Resources" slug={slug} seo={seo}>
  <Fragment slot="header" { ...data }>
    <Header { ...data } />
  </Fragment>
  <section class="content">
    <p>Thanks for attending my AI Engineer Melbourne 2026 talk, <em>Fail fast,
      fix faster</em>. Below you&apos;ll find the slides, benchmark materials,
      model references and extra reading around the core idea: once a model is
      competent enough, loop speed and validation quality start to matter as
      much as raw intelligence.</p>

    <h3>Talk slides and notes</h3>

    <p>You can view the slides below, or <a
      href="https://aieng26.ajf.io/">visit the slide site</a> for the large
      version.</p>

    <p class="mediacontainer"><iframe title="Fail fast, fix faster slides"
      src="https://aieng26.ajf.io/?embed"></iframe></p>

    <p>Slides made with <a href="https://github.com/ajfisher/presso">presso</a></p>

    <p>The rest of this page collects the context, benchmark materials, model
      references and follow-on reading from the talk.</p>

    <h3>Resources</h3>

    <p>Start with the context links if you want the narrative, or jump to the
      benchmark materials if you want the code, results and model references.</p>

    <h4>Talk context</h4>

    <p>These links give the framing for the talk, including the conference
      info, the article that started the experiment, and the loop-oriented
      thinking behind the benchmark design.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><a
        href="https://webdirections.org/ai-engineer/speakers/aj-fisher.php"
        >Web Directions AI Engineer listing</a> for the talk and conference
        details.</li>
      <li><a
        href="/2026/02/26/mercury-2-diffusion-agents/">Mercury 2
        won&apos;t outthink frontier models but diffusion might out-iterate
        them</a>, the original article that kicked off the talk.</li>
      <li><a href="https://ghuntley.com/loop/">Everything is a Ralph loop</a>
        by Geoffrey Huntley, which framed the persistent agent loop pattern
        used in the benchmark.</li>
      <li><a href="https://github.com/karpathy/autoresearch">AutoResearch</a>
        by Andrej Karpathy, which explores a similar cheap-experiment,
        measurable-feedback loop in model training.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Benchmark materials</h4>

    <p>The benchmark uses a small quote approval API task with an OpenAPI
      contract and a fast validation harness. Each model gets up to 15 turns,
      receives targeted failure feedback, and is scored across repeated runs.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><a
        href="https://github.com/ajfisher/demo-dumb-fast-agents">Benchmark
        repository: ajfisher/demo-dumb-fast-agents</a></li>
      <li><a
        href="https://github.com/ajfisher/demo-dumb-fast-agents/blob/main/agent/evals/talk-master-summary.md"
        >Talk benchmark summary</a></li>
      <li><a
        href="https://github.com/ajfisher/demo-dumb-fast-agents/blob/main/agent/evals/matrix.talk-battery.json"
        >Final talk benchmark matrix</a></li>
      <li><a
        href="https://github.com/ajfisher/demo-dumb-fast-agents/blob/main/docs/spec.md"
        >Quote approval API task specification</a></li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Headline benchmark results</h4>

    <p>The headline result is not that Mercury 2 is the smartest model,
      but that a fast enough model can compound improvement loops very quickly
      when the validation harness is tight.</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Model</th>
          <th>Pass</th>
          <th>Median turns</th>
          <th>Mean time to pass</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Mercury 2</td>
          <td>10/10</td>
          <td>2</td>
          <td>6s</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>GPT-5.4 mini</td>
          <td>10/10</td>
          <td>1</td>
          <td>41s</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>GPT-5.4</td>
          <td>10/10</td>
          <td>1</td>
          <td>88s</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>GPT-4.1 mini</td>
          <td>10/10</td>
          <td>2</td>
          <td>54s</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Gemini 2.5 Flash</td>
          <td>8/10</td>
          <td>4</td>
          <td>77s</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Gemma 4 31B cloud</td>
          <td>10/10</td>
          <td>5</td>
          <td>133s</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Qwen3 Coder 480B cloud</td>
          <td>7/10</td>
          <td>5</td>
          <td>611s</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Orthrus Qwen3 8B MLX</td>
          <td>0/5</td>
          <td>n/a</td>
          <td>n/a</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Phi3</td>
          <td>0/5</td>
          <td>n/a</td>
          <td>n/a</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h4>Model cards and provider docs</h4>

    <p>These are the model and provider references for the systems included in
      the benchmark runs.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><a href="https://www.inceptionlabs.ai/models">Mercury 2</a> from
        Inception Labs.</li>
      <li><a href="https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/models/gpt-5.4/"
        >GPT-5.4</a> and the <a
        href="https://openai.com/index/gpt-5-4-thinking-system-card/">GPT-5.4
        Thinking system card</a>.</li>
      <li><a
        href="https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/models/gpt-5.4-mini"
        >GPT-5.4 mini</a>.</li>
      <li><a
        href="https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/models/gpt-4.1-mini"
        >GPT-4.1 mini</a>.</li>
      <li><a href="https://ai.google.dev/gemini-api/docs/models">Gemini 2.5
        Flash</a>.</li>
      <li><a href="https://ollama.com/library/gemma4%3A31b-cloud">Gemma 4
        31B cloud on Ollama</a> and the <a
        href="https://deepmind.google/models/gemma/gemma-4/">Gemma 4 model
        page</a>.</li>
      <li><a href="https://ollama.com/library/qwen3-coder">Qwen3 Coder 480B
        cloud on Ollama</a> and the <a
        href="https://qwenlm.github.io/blog/qwen3-coder/">Qwen3 Coder launch
        post</a>.</li>
      <li><a href="https://huggingface.co/chiennv/Orthrus-Qwen3-8B">Orthrus
        Qwen3 8B</a>, plus the <a
        href="https://github.com/chiennv2000/orthrus">Orthrus code</a> and
        <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2605.12825">paper</a>.</li>
      <li><a href="https://ollama.com/library/phi3">Phi3 on Ollama</a> and
        the <a
        href="https://huggingface.co/microsoft/Phi-3-mini-128k-instruct">Phi-3
        Mini 128K Instruct model card</a>.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Mercury and diffusion LLM references</h4>

    <p>These cover the Mercury launch material and the underlying diffusion
      language model work that makes the fast iteration loop interesting.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><a href="https://www.inceptionlabs.ai/blog/introducing-mercury-2"
        >Introducing Mercury 2</a> from Inception Labs.</li>
      <li><a href="https://www.inceptionlabs.ai/blog/introducing-mercury"
        >Introducing Mercury</a>, the earlier Mercury Coder launch post.</li>
      <li><a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.17298">Mercury: Ultra-Fast
        Language Models Based on Diffusion</a>.</li>
      <li><a
        href="https://www.inceptionlabs.ai/blog/rise-of-realtime-subagents"
        >Mercury 2 and the Rise of Real-time Subagents</a>.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Extra references worth reading</h4>

    <p>These are useful additions if you want to go deeper on agent
      evaluation, repeatable workflows and feedback-driven optimisation.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><a href="https://inspect.aisi.org.uk/">Inspect</a>, the UK AI
        Security Institute evaluation framework, for thinking about repeatable
        LLM and agent evals.</li>
      <li><a href="https://www.swebench.com/">SWE-bench</a> and <a
        href="https://huggingface.co/datasets/princeton-nlp/SWE-bench_Verified"
        >SWE-bench Verified</a>, useful references for repository-level
        coding agent evaluation.</li>
      <li><a href="https://github.com/openai/evals">OpenAI Evals</a>, useful
        as a reference point for building repeatable, code-backed eval suites.</li>
      <li><a
        href="https://www.anthropic.com/engineering/claude-code-best-practices"
        >Claude Code best practices</a>, especially the parts on context,
        verification and repeatable workflows.</li>
      <li><a href="https://dspy.ai/">DSPy</a>, which is relevant when you want
        to optimise an LLM workflow against a metric rather than hand-tune
        prompts forever.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Where to next?</h4>

    <p>The <a href="/">home page</a> will give you featured articles and recent
      posts.</p>
    <p>You can also check out <a href="/blog/">the full list of articles</a>
      that have ever been published.</p>
  </section>
  <PostAttribution {...data} />
  <Fragment slot="postdata">
      <PostData { ...data } />
  </Fragment>
</BaseLayout>
